platinum-etoposide in extensive-stage SCLC (CASPIAN): a brief report. JTO Clin Res Rep. 2022;3</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC9204731</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">35719865</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Shiraishi Y., Shimose T., Tsuchiya-Kawano Y., et al. Forthcoming phase II study of durvalumab (MEDI4736) plus chemotherapy for small cell lung cancer with brain metastases. Cancer Manag Res. 2022;14:3449&#x2013;3453.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC9760036</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">36540201</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events (CTCAE) Version 5.0. U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, National Institutes of Health, National Cancer Institute. 2017. https://ctep.cancer.gov/protocoldevelopment/electronic_applications/docs/ctcae_v5_quick_reference_5x7.pdf Available at.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>Lukas R.V., Gondi V., Kamson D.O., Kumthekar P., Salgia R. State-of-the-art considerations in small cell lung cancer brain metastases. Oncotarget. 2017;8:71223&#x2013;71233.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC5642633</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">29050358</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Shimokawa T., Okamoto H., Machida R., et al. Carboplatin and irinotecan (CI) vs. carboplatin and etoposide (CE) for the treatment of extended-stage small-cell lung cancer in an elderly population: a phase II/III randomized control trial. Lung Cancer. 2023;181</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">37156212</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">40602202</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>08</Month><Day>09</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>08</Month><Day>14</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1872-8332</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>206</Volume><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Aug</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Lung cancer (Amsterdam, Netherlands)</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Lung Cancer</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Durvalumab plus irinotecan&#xa0;+&#xa0;cisplatin for untreated extensive-stage small cell lung cancer: REBORN, phase II study (WJOG13520L).</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>108637</StartPage><MedlinePgn>108637</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.lungcan.2025.108637</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0169-5002(25)00529-X</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="INTRODUCTION" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">PD-L1 inhibitors combined etoposide-platinum (EP) are standard first-line treatments for extensive-stage small-cell lung cancer (ES-SCLC). However, their efficacy remains suboptimal. Irinotecan-cisplatin (IP) is optional regimen for ES-SCLC, and irinotecan has shown potential immunostimulatory activity. This study evaluated the efficacy and safety of IP plus durvalumab in untreated ES-SCLC.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Eligible patients (aged 20-74&#xa0;years; PS 0-1 received four cycles of IP (irinotecan 60&#xa0;mg/m<sup>2</sup>, days 1,8,15 and cisplatin 60&#xa0;mg/m<sup>2</sup>, day 1) with durvalumab 1500&#xa0;mg, followed by durvalumab 1500&#xa0;mg every 4&#xa0;weeks. Primary endpoint was the 12-month progression-free survival (PFS) rate, assessed by an independent central review (ICR).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Between May 2021 and Nov 2022, 42 patients (median age, 66&#xa0;years; 76.2&#xa0;% were male; 31.0&#xa0;% had PS 0) were enrolled. The 12-month PFS rate by ICR was 18.8&#xa0;% (90&#xa0;% CI, 9.3-30.8&#xa0;%), with a median PFS of 5.7&#xa0;months (95&#xa0;% CI, 4.9-7.6&#xa0;months). Median overall survival (OS) was 16.9&#xa0;months (95&#xa0;% CI, 11.8-NE), and the 12-month OS rate was 65.8&#xa0;% (95&#xa0;% CI, 49.1-78.1). Confirmed overall response rate (ORR) was 65.9&#xa0;%, and disease control rate (DCR) was 85.4&#xa0;%. Grade &#x2265;3 adverse events (AEs) occurred in 73.8&#xa0;%, including two grade 5 (2.4&#xa0;%; pneumonitis and hepatitis). Pneumonitis occurred in 4.8&#xa0;% (grade 1 and 5), while diarrhea of grade 3 or more occurred in 7.1&#xa0;% patients.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">The REBORN study did not demonstrate the expected efficacy of IP plus durvalumab in untreated ES-SCLC, with its efficacy and safety generally comparable to those of EP plus durvalumab.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 The Author(s). Published by Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Tachihara</LastName><ForeName>Motoko</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Respiratory Medicine, Department of Internal Medicine, Kobe University Graduate School of Medicine, Kobe, Japan. Electronic address: mt0318@med.kobe-u.ac.jp.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Shoda</LastName><ForeName>Hiroyasu</ForeName><Initials>H</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Respiratory Medicine, Hiroshima Citizens Hospital, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Akazawa</LastName><ForeName>Yuki</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Thoracic Oncology, NHO Osaka Toneyama Medical Center, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Ota</LastName><ForeName>Takayo</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Izumi City General Hospital, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastNa